The Latinitas ol the latini coloniarii had conferred the commercium without the connubium, i. e. the power ol holding property and engaging in commerce under the peculiar forms and protection oi Roman law, and ol making a testament valid iure civili. But these rights were seriously curtailed, in the case os Latini luniani, by the lex lunia Norbana, which (Gaius i. 22-24 Ulpian, reg. ao. 8) deprived them of the privileges os making a will, being named testamentary guardians, and benefiting under the will of another person. Consequently, when a Latinus Iunianus died, as he could have no suus heres or agnete, his whole property went ‘iure quodammodo peculii' to his patron; Bk. iii. 7. 4 inl. Justinian repealed the lex lunia, and as to the modes oi manumission to which it had related, he enacted that they should make a slave a lull citizen provided they were evidenced hy five witnesses; Cod. 7. 6. The alii multi modi alluded to in ξ 1 are specified in the same constitution : among them are the formal designation oi the slave by the master as his son, and the delivery to him of the docu- ments by which his servitude could be proved. There were numerous modes in which a Latinus could attain the civitas ; see Gaius i. 28-35, and hir. Poste’s notes.
